
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `editor` (virayeshgar) baraye baz kardan va virayesh kardan file-haye matni (text files) be kar miravad.  In dastoor obiate-i nist, va obiatan bayad ba yek virayeshgare matni mesle `nano`, `vim`, ya `emacs` hamrah bashad. Agar editor e moshakhas shode nist, az virayeshgare pishfarz estefade mikonad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `editor filename` --> 📝 Baz kardan file ba virayeshgare pishfarz.
    🔹 `EDITOR="nano" editor filename` --> ✒️ Baz kardan file ba virayeshgare `nano`. (mohammadood ast faghat dar hamin dastoor)
    🔹 `EDITOR="vim" editor filename` --> 💻 Baz kardan file ba virayeshgare `vim`. (mohammadood ast faghat dar hamin dastoor)

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ editor myfile.txt

    🔹  Baz kardan `myfile.txt` ba virayeshgare pishfarz.

    $ EDITOR="nano" editor myfile.txt

    🔹  Baz kardan `myfile.txt` ba virayeshgare `nano`.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ EDITOR="nano" editor newfile.txt

    🔹  Agar `newfile.txt` vojood nadashte bashad, `nano` yek file jadid misazad.  Ba save kardan file, in file dar directory kari save mishavad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `editor` command is used to open and edit text files. This command is typically an abstraction, and it usually needs to be coupled with a specific text editor like `nano`, `vim`, or `emacs`. If no editor is specified, it uses the default editor configured in the system.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `editor filename` --> 📝 Open the file with the default editor.
    🔹 `EDITOR="nano" editor filename` --> ✒️ Open the file using the `nano` editor (only effective for this command).
    🔹 `EDITOR="vim" editor filename` --> 💻 Open the file using the `vim` editor (only effective for this command).

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ editor myfile.txt

    🔹 Open `myfile.txt` using the default editor.

    $ EDITOR="nano" editor myfile.txt

    🔹 Open `myfile.txt` using the `nano` editor.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ EDITOR="nano" editor newfile.txt

    🔹 If `newfile.txt` does not exist, `nano` creates a new file. Saving the file will save it in the current working directory.
